<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span></h2>
<div class="reflist" style="list-style-type: decimal;">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-3"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">See also: <a href="Thomas_Jefferson_and_religion" title="Thomas Jefferson and religion">Thomas Jefferson and religion</a></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-25"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-25">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">His other properties included <a href="Shadwell_(Virginia)" title="Shadwell (Virginia)">Shadwell</a>, Tufton, Lego, Pantops and his retreat, <a href="Poplar_Forest" title="Poplar Forest">Poplar Forest</a> He also owned an unimproved mountaintop, Montalto.<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24"><span>[</span>23<span>]</span></a></sup></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-70"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-70">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Jefferson's draft said: "where powers are assumed [by the federal government] which have not been delegated, a nullification of the act is the rightful remedy: that every State has a natural right in cases not within the compact, (casus non fœderis) to nullify of their own authority all assumptions of power by others within their limits." See <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.constitution.org/cons/kent1798.htm">Jefferson's draft of the Kentucky Resolutions of 1798</a>.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-76"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-76">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">This electoral process problem was addressed by the <a href="Twelfth_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution" title="Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution">Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution</a> in 1804.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-129"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-129">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The cemetery is separately owned and operated by the <a href="Monticello_Association" title="Monticello Association">Monticello Association</a>, a lineage society that is not affiliated with the Thomas Jefferson Foundation that runs the estate as a public history site.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-170"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-170">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Jefferson's original draft of the Declaration of Independence included this denunciation but it was striken by Congress for fear it would only antagonize the British Crown -- it was the largest clause removed.</span></li>
</ol>
</div>
